{
    public CustomersTraining(AppDbContext db, Dictionary<string, int> slugMap) : base(db, slugMap) { }

    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customers Overview",
            Slug = "customers-overview",
            Summary = "What the Customers module does, the lifecycle-driven detail tabs, contacts, addresses, credit management, and how customers connect to quotes, orders, jobs, and invoices.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","contacts","addresses","credit"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customers Overview\n\nThe Customers module is your central hub for every customer your shop works with. It tracks their contact people, addresses, credit status, estimates, quotes, sales orders, jobs, invoices, and full activity history. Every customer gets its own detail page, and the tabs on that page adapt to where the customer is in their relationship with your shop — giving you a complete view.\n\n### Customer List Page\n\nThe main Customers page shows every customer in a searchable, sortable table. Filter by active or inactive status, or search by name, company, email, or phone. Click any row to open that customer's detail page. The Add Customer button opens a quick form for name, company, email, and phone.\n\n### Customer Detail Page — Tabs That Adapt\n\nEach customer's detail page opens with a header showing their name, company, contact info, an active or inactive label, and an accounting badge when the record is synced with a provider like QuickBooks.\n\n**The tabs are not fixed — they change with where the customer is in their journey** (based on whether they're active and how much open business they have). Overview is always first and Activity is always last; the tabs in between vary:\n- **Active** (an active customer with open estimates, quotes, orders, jobs, or invoices): Overview, Contacts, Addresses, Estimates, Quotes, Orders, Jobs, Invoices, Pricing, Interactions, Activity (11 tabs)\n- **Prospect** (active but no open business yet): Overview, Contacts, Addresses, Estimates, Quotes, Interactions, Activity (7 tabs — Orders, Jobs, Invoices, and Pricing stay hidden until there's business)\n- **Archived** (an inactive customer): Overview, Contacts, Addresses, Invoices, Interactions, Activity (6 tabs — a read-only history view; Invoices stays in case of unpaid balances)\n\nTabs you've turned off in your setup (Contacts, Addresses, Interactions) drop out too. The sections below describe each tab you may see.\n\n#### Stats Bar\n\nA clickable stats bar below the header shows live totals:\n- **Open Estimates** — how many estimates are still open\n- **Open Quotes** — how many quotes are active\n- **Open Orders** — how many sales orders are in progress\n- **Active Jobs** — how many jobs are currently on the board\n- **Outstanding** — the total dollar amount of unpaid invoices\n- **YTD Revenue** — total revenue from this customer so far this year\n\nClick any stat to jump to the matching tab.\n\n#### Overview\n\nShows account details (name, company, email, phone, status, customer-since date), accounting info when connected, and the Credit Status card.\n\n**The Credit Status card** shows:\n- A risk level: Low, Medium, High, or On Hold\n- A credit-hold banner with the reason and a Release button (when the customer is on hold)\n- Credit limit, open balance owed, pending orders, total exposure, available credit, and how much of the limit is used\n- A usage bar that turns red when the customer is over their limit\n- A Place Hold button to block new orders, which asks for a reason\n\n#### Contacts\n\nManage the people you deal with at this customer. Each contact appears as a card showing their initials, name (Last, First), role, email, phone, and a Primary badge. You can add, edit, and remove contacts. Contact roles come from your setup, so you can tailor them.\n\n#### Interactions\n\nLog and track your dealings with the customer — calls, emails, meetings, and notes. Each entry records the type, subject, contact, who logged it, date, duration, and notes. Filter by contact or type.\n\n#### Addresses\n\nView every address on file. Each address card shows its type (Billing, Shipping, and so on), a Default badge when it applies, and the full address.\n\n#### Estimates\n\nRough ballpark figures for possible work. Each estimate has a title, description, estimated amount, valid-until date, status (Draft, Sent, Accepted, Declined, Expired), and notes. Turn an estimate into a formal quote with the convert button.\n\n#### Quotes\n\nFirm, line-by-line price commitments. The table shows the quote number, status, total, expiration date, and created date. Click a row to open the full quote.\n\n#### Orders\n\nSales orders for this customer. The table shows the order number, status, total, requested date, and created date. Click a row to open the order.\n\n#### Jobs\n\nAll jobs on the board linked to this customer. The table shows the job title, stage, due date, and created date. Click a row to open the job.\n\n#### Invoices\n\nInvoices sent to this customer. The table shows the invoice number, status, total, due date, and created date. Click a row to open the invoice.\n\n#### Pricing\n\nSpecial pricing you've negotiated with this customer (Active customers only). Office Managers can adjust it right here.\n\n#### Activity\n\nA time-ordered history of every change, comment, and event for this customer.\n\n### How Customers Connect to Everything Else\n\n**Quote-to-cash flow:** Customer → Estimate → Quote → Sales Order → Job → Shipment → Invoice → Payment. Every step links back to the customer.\n\n**Jobs:** When you create a job on the board, you can assign it to a customer. Their Jobs tab then shows every linked job.\n\n**Credit management:** The Credit Status card watches how much the customer owes plus pending orders against their credit limit. When a customer is on hold, new orders are blocked until you release the hold.\n\n**Accounting:** When connected to QuickBooks or another provider, the customer record stays in sync both ways, and the provider details show on the Overview tab.\n\n### When to Use Customers\n\n- When you're setting up a new customer for the first time\n- When you need a customer's full history (orders, jobs, invoices)\n- When you're checking credit before accepting a new order\n- When you're logging a call, email, or meeting with a contact\n- When you're managing billing and shipping addresses\n- When you're creating estimates or turning them into quotes","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
