        // ── Customer-Specific Pricing (Article) ──────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer-Specific Pricing",
            Slug = "customers-pricing",
            Summary = "How the Pricing tab works: building negotiated price lists, adding quantity-break entries, inline-editing prices, and bulk-importing entries from CSV.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","pricing","price-list","csv"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customer-Specific Pricing\n\nThe **Pricing** tab on a customer's detail page is where you record the special prices that customer gets, overriding the standard catalog price. It shows up for **Active** customers (Office Managers use it to adjust a customer's pricing on the spot). Prospect and Archived customers don't have a Pricing tab.\n\n### Price Lists\n\nA customer can have one or more **price lists**. A price list is a named group of prices with an optional date range and a default setting.\n\n- Click **+ New List** to create one. You'll enter a **Name** (required), Description, an **Effective From** and **Effective To** date range, a **Default** switch, and an **Active** switch.\n- If a customer has more than one list, a **list picker** appears at the top of the tab so you can switch between them.\n- The header shows the selected list's name and its date range (or 'Always' when both dates are blank).\n- Use the **edit** button to change the list's details, or the **delete** button to remove it. Deleting a list that has prices in it warns you how many will be removed first.\n- When there's no list yet, you'll see a **Create First List** button.\n\n### Price List Entries (Quantity Breaks)\n\nEach price list holds **entries**. An entry sets a **unit price** for a **part** at or above a **minimum quantity** — that's how volume pricing works: the entry with the highest minimum quantity that's still at or below the amount ordered is the one that applies.\n\n- Click **+ Add** to open the entry form. Pick the **Part** (start typing to search, or create a new part on the spot), enter the **Unit Price** (required), the **Min Quantity** (required — the amount this price kicks in at), and the **Currency** (required). An optional **Notes** field adds context.\n- On an existing entry, the **Part** is locked — to price a different part, add a new entry.\n- **Quick in-place editing:** in the entries table you can click a **Min Quantity** or **Unit Price** value to change it right there. Press **Enter** to save or **Escape** to cancel; you'll see a brief spinner while it saves and a marker if the value isn't valid. This is the fastest way to tweak a single number without opening the form.\n- Each row also has **edit** and **delete** buttons for full changes and removals.\n\n### Bulk Import from a Spreadsheet\n\nWhen you have many prices to load at once, use **Import** (the upload button in the entries header):\n\n1. **Pick a file** — drag a spreadsheet file onto the drop area or click **Browse**. A **Download Template** link gives you the correct column layout.\n2. **Preview** — the system reads the file and shows a preview with a summary of how many rows will be **added**, **updated**, or have an **error**. Each row is tagged, and error rows show the reason (for example, an unknown part number or a bad price).\n3. **Apply** — the Apply button stays grayed out while any row has an error. Fix the file and upload again, or go ahead once it's clean. Use **Back** to return to the file picker.\n\nImported rows are matched to existing entries by part and minimum quantity, so re-importing an updated file updates the matching rows instead of creating duplicates.\n\n### How This Pricing Is Used Later\n\nThese negotiated prices flow into the rest of quote-to-cash: when you add a line to a sales order (or quote) for this customer and pick a part, the unit price fills in automatically from the customer's matching price for the amount ordered. That keeps negotiated pricing consistent without anyone retyping it on every order.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Customer-Specific Pricing (QuickRef) ─────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer Pricing Field Reference",
            Slug = "customers-pricing-field-reference",
            Summary = "Reference for the Pricing tab: price list fields, entry fields, inline-edit behavior, the CSV bulk-import flow, and how price lists resolve onto order lines.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","pricing","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"Customer Pricing Field Reference","groups":[{"heading":"Where to Find It","items":[{"label":"Pricing tab","value":"On a customer's detail page, for Active customers only. Hidden for Prospect and Archived customers."},{"label":"Who uses it","value":"Office Managers (plus Admins and Managers) adjust a customer's pricing on the spot."}]},{"heading":"Price List Form Fields","items":[{"label":"Name (required)","value":"Up to 100 characters. Names the price list (for example, '2026 Contract Pricing')."},{"label":"Description","value":"Optional. Free-form notes about the list."},{"label":"Effective From","value":"Optional. The date the list starts applying."},{"label":"Effective To","value":"Optional. The date the list stops applying. The header shows 'Always' when both dates are blank, or 'From X' / 'Until Y' when only one is set."},{"label":"Default","value":"An on/off switch. Marks this as the customer's default list, picked automatically when the tab opens."},{"label":"Active","value":"An on/off switch. Inactive lists are kept but not applied."}]},{"heading":"Price List Entry Form Fields","items":[{"label":"Part","value":"Start typing to search by part number or name. Required. You can create a new part on the spot. Locked when editing an existing entry."},{"label":"Unit Price (required)","value":"The negotiated price per unit at this quantity break."},{"label":"Min Quantity (required)","value":"The amount this price kicks in at. The highest minimum still at or below the amount ordered wins."},{"label":"Currency (required)","value":"The currency for this entry's price."},{"label":"Notes","value":"Optional. Context for the entry."}]},{"heading":"Inline Cell Editing","items":[{"label":"Editable values","value":"The Min Quantity and Unit Price columns. Click a value to change it right there."},{"label":"Save / cancel","value":"Enter saves; Escape cancels. A spinner shows while saving, and a marker appears if the value isn't valid."},{"label":"Row actions","value":"The edit button opens the full entry form; the delete button removes the entry after you confirm."}]},{"heading":"CSV Bulk Import","items":[{"label":"Import button","value":"The upload button in the entries header. Opens the two-step import for the selected list."},{"label":"Download Template","value":"A link on the first step that downloads a spreadsheet with the correct columns."},{"label":"Preview summary","value":"After the file is read, shows how many rows will be added, updated, or have an error, with a message on each error row."},{"label":"Apply","value":"Grayed out while any row has an error. Applies the import; rows are matched by part and minimum quantity, so re-imports update instead of duplicating."},{"label":"Back / Cancel","value":"Back returns to the file picker from the preview; Cancel closes the window."}]},{"heading":"List Management","items":[{"label":"+ New List","value":"Creates a price list. When there are none, you'll see a Create First List button instead."},{"label":"List picker","value":"Appears at the top only when the customer has more than one list."},{"label":"Edit / Delete list","value":"The edit and delete buttons in the entries header. Deleting a list that has prices warns you about the count first."}]},{"heading":"Downstream Use","items":[{"label":"Order/Quote line auto-fill","value":"Picking a part on a sales order or quote line for this customer fills in the unit price from the matching price for the amount ordered."}]}]}"""
        });

        // ── Customer Portal Access (Article) ─────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customer Portal Access",
            Slug = "customers-portal-access",
            Summary = "How to provision, enable, and disable external portal logins for customer contacts from the /customers/portal-access admin page.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 9,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers/portal-access"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","portal","access","contacts"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Customer Portal Access\n\nThe **Portal Access** page is where you give your customers' contacts a login to the external customer portal. From one screen you can see who has access, set up new logins, and turn access on or off — for all your customers in one place.\n\n### The Access List\n\nThe page is a single table listing every contact who's been set up, with:\n- **Contact Name** (Last, First)\n- **Customer** — the company the contact belongs to\n- **Email** — their portal login (a contact's email *is* their username)\n- **Last Login** — when they last signed in, or 'Never signed in' if they haven't yet\n- **Created** — when their access was set up\n- **Enabled** — an on/off switch to turn the login on or off\n\nClick a row to jump to that customer's **Contacts** tab. The table is searchable and sortable like any other.\n\n### Setting Up Access for a Contact\n\nClick **Provision Portal Access** to open the setup window:\n\n1. It loads the list of contacts you can add — those who have an **email** (required, since email is the login) and don't already have portal access.\n2. Pick a contact and confirm. The system creates their access. It's safe to do this for a contact who already has access — nothing breaks.\n3. If there are no contacts to add, the window tells you so. Usually that means everyone with an email already has access, or no contacts have an email yet. Add an email to the contact first (on the customer's Contacts tab), then set up access.\n\n### Turning Access On and Off\n\nThe **Enabled** switch on each row turns a contact's login on or off without removing them:\n- Switch it **off** to immediately stop a contact from signing in (say, they left the company) while keeping the record and their sign-in history.\n- Switch it **on** to restore access.\n- The switch pauses briefly while the change saves, and a confirmation message names the affected contact.\n\n### Key Points\n\n- **Email is required** — a contact with no email can't be set up, because the portal uses email as the username.\n- **Access is per person, not per company** — each individual gets their own login. One customer company can have several portal users.\n- **Turning it off is reversible** — it keeps the record and history, so re-enabling isn't starting over.\n- **The list spans all customers** — this page shows portal users across every customer in one place, which is why it lives under the Customers hub rather than on a single customer's page.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Customers — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "customers-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case and ancillary reference for Customers: accounting boundary, capability gating of tabs/credit card, Overview compliance/reference flags, recent-communications auto-logging, Segments/Import placeholders, completeness chip, and price-list effective dates.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/customers"]""",
            Tags = """["customers","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Accounting Sync Behavior\n\nA customer's financial fields follow the accounting boundary. When an outside accounting provider (such as QuickBooks Online) is connected, the customer record stays in sync both ways and the provider becomes the source of truth for the money side. The Overview tab then shows an accounting badge along with the provider name and reference. Your own data in the app — addresses, contacts, interactions, price lists, sales orders, and quotes — stays editable no matter what. Only the accounting-managed areas (invoices, payments, aging, credit terms) become read-only or hidden when a provider is connected. On their own (no provider), those areas are fully editable.\n\n## Turning Tabs and the Credit Card On or Off\n\nThe tabs in the middle of the customer detail page can each be turned on or off in your setup. When one is turned off, that tab simply doesn't appear:\n\n- **Contacts**\n- **Addresses**\n- **Interactions**\n\nOverview and Activity are always shown. The whole Customers area and portal access can also be turned on or off. The **Credit Status card** on the Overview tab can be turned off too — shops that take payment up front and don't extend credit can hide it, which also removes the Place Hold button and the credit figures. The same setting hides the credit fields in the customer form.\n\n## Compliance and Reference Flags on Overview\n\nThe Overview tab has a set of compliance switches plus a sales-reference switch:\n\n- **Compliance flags** — FDA regulated, aerospace, automotive, and ITAR controlled. Each is its own on/off switch with a short explanation. These flags can be used to group customers into segments (for example, all aerospace customers).\n- **Reference flags** — one switch marks the customer as OK to use as a sales reference, and a notes field holds any context. If you edit the notes and try to leave without saving, you'll be asked to confirm before your changes are discarded.\n\nSwitches save right away and let you know if anything fails.\n\n## Automatic Communication Logging\n\nThe Overview tab includes a **Recent Communications** panel. It pulls from the customer's activity and shows communication-type entries: auto-logged emails tied to a contact, sent and received messages, and interactions you logged by hand on the Interactions tab. The five most recent show here; the full list is on the Activity tab. Because customers can log interactions by hand, the empty state here is just informational (on leads it prompts you to connect a mailbox).\n\n## Segments and Import (Coming Soon)\n\nTwo pages under the Customers hub are **previews** for now — the full versions ship later:\n\n- **Segments** — shows a few example saved segments (like a high-value aerospace group) so you can see how the feature will work before the real segment builder is available.\n- **Import** — a placeholder for the bulk-import wizard; the real upload and column-mapping flow comes in a later release.\n\nYou can open both today, but they don't save anything yet.\n\n## Completeness Indicator\n\nThe customer list and detail header show a completeness indicator for each customer:\n\n- A small inline badge.\n- A fuller chip you can click to see a list of what's still missing (which recommended fields or relationships a customer record doesn't have yet).\n\nOn the list, the completeness column is hidden by default and you can turn it on. Completeness is worked out for each customer, so the gaps reflect the recommended details a record is still missing.\n\n## Price-List Date Ranges\n\nA customer's price lists (on the Pricing tab, for Office Managers) can carry an optional date range: an effective-from and an effective-to date, both optional. When you set both, the effective-to date must be after the effective-from date, or the form flags an error. Blank dates mean \"Always\"; a single date shows as \"From X\" or \"Until Y\" in the list header. This lets you stage next year's contract pricing ahead of its start date without overwriting the current list.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Customers training modules");
    }
